Then, the parameters affecting the sensitivity of the method were carefully examined and optimized to improve the response of NEB to B CQDs. These parameters include the interaction time, the volume of buffer used and the pH value, as well as the concentration of B@CQD. The reaction of B@CQD with NEB was tested at different pH ranges from 6 to 7.8 to determine how pH affects the results (Fig. 4 b). It was observed that the use of pH 6.8 and 1.5 ± 0.25 mL of BR buffer produced the maximum fluorescence intensity of B CQDs (
Figure S4
).

Robustness was evaluated utilizing minor changes in the proposed methodology settings, including B@CQDs concentration, the buffer volume & pH, and interaction time. Those minor modifications had a non-significant influence on the outcomes of recovery results of NEB determination (

                           Table S1

                        ).

Content uniformity testing is another major approach in the quality control of pharmaceutical tablet dosage forms. The drug content of each manufactured tablet must fall falls within a specified range around the claimed labeled content. This, in turn, warrants the uniformity of dosing in each unit [30,31]. Content uniformity testing could be tedious and time-consuming process when complex approaches are followed [40]. However, using B@CQDs method ideally suited with high throughput and cost-effectiveness. The uniformity test was applied according to the USP guideline protocol. The acceptance value (AV) was then calculated. AV was calculated by multiplying the standard deviation of percentage recoveries obtained by 2.4, which was found to be lower than the permitted maximum acceptance value (L1), indicating consistent batch production of NEB. (
                        Table 5

                        ).
